Why data vis?

Why data vis?

Criticisms of that story

  • Hindsight bias
  • Temperature not the only independent variable
  • O-ring not the only cause of failure
  • Still a great story

ggplot2

  • By Hadley Wickham, again
  • Ridiculously powerful visualisation tool
  • Great for exploration; produces publication-quality plots
  • Extends to ggvis, allowing interactive charts (similar to D3)
  • Lots of add-ons, especially useful are themes from ggthemes (Economist, WSJ, Tufte, fivethirtyeight, etc.)

What you will need

  • install.packages("ggplot2")
  • install.packages("ggthemes")
  • load("super_data.RData"); should have downloaded this for homework
  • Lots of time with stackoverflow.com 
load("super_data.RData")
library(ggplot2); library(dplyr)

Introduction to ggplot

  • Data needs to be tidy (long-form)
    • This is the first thing that gets people frustrated
  • Aesthetics are the various aspects of the chart
    • Each aesthetic has only one column
  • Using it with dplyr saves time and effort

ggplot syntax

data %>% ggplot(aes(x = xcolumn, y = ycolumn, colour = colourcolumn)) +
  geom_point(options in here) +
  geom_smooth(options in here)

The scatter chart with geom_point()

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point()

Some questions

  • How many times is each fund represented on the chart?
  • Is there a relationship between fees and returns?

The scatter chart with geom_point()

apra.sr.full %>%

Adding colour

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return, colour = as.factor(Year))) +

Adding size

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return, colour = as.factor(Year), size = Real.FUM)) +
  geom_point()

The smoother

  • Often we want to check if there is a relationship between variables
  • We may also want to check to see if the relationship appears to be linear
  • In Excel, we add a regression line
  • In ggplot, we add a smoother. Two options:
    • Default: a loess curve, which is basically a local regression line.
    • method = "lm" gives us a linear regression.
    • Both methods include confidence intervals for the intercept and slope

The smoother

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

The smoother adopts groups/colours

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return, colour = as.factor(Year))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

The smoother allows linear regression

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return, colour = as.factor(Year))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Sometimes it's helpful to plot densities

apra.sr.full %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Rate_of_return, colour = as.factor(Year))) +
  geom_density()

Faceting

  • The idea here is that sometimes we want a different plot for each group
    • The last plot was a bit hard to read, no?

Syntax:

 + facet_grid(verticalvar ~ horizontalvar)

 + facet_grid(verticalvar ~ .) # Only vertical facet

 + facet_grid(.~horizontalvar) # Only horizontal facet

Faceting 1

apra.sr.full %>% filter(!is.na(Average.fees)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  facet_grid(Year ~., scales = "free")

Faceting exercise

  • Add another facet (horizontal) for Fund_type
  • Do fees impact returns similarly for all fund types?

Alpha

  • Alpha refers to how opaque a certain geometry is, with 0 being fully transparent, and 1 being fully solid.
  • When using many data points, it can be helpful to decrease alpha, (unless the point is to draw attention to outliers)

Alpha

apra.sr.full %>% filter(!is.na(Average.fees)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + # Add your alpha here
  geom_smooth() +
  facet_grid(Year ~., scales = "free")

Themes

  • The default ggplot2 theme is horrific
  • ggthemes has some great add-on themes.
    • Use + theme_whatever
  • I personally write my own themes, which are built up on theme_bw()

Adding a nice theme

library(ggthemes)
apra.sr.full %>% filter(!is.na(Average.fees)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth() +facet_grid(Year ~., scales = "free") +
  theme_economist()

Adding a nice theme

library(ggthemes)
apra.sr.full %>% filter(!is.na(Average.fees)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth() +facet_grid(Year ~., scales = "free") +
  theme_wsj()

Adding a nice theme

library(ggthemes)
apra.sr.full %>% filter(!is.na(Average.fees)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Average.fees, y = Rate_of_return)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth() +facet_grid(Year ~., scales = "free") +
  theme_fivethirtyeight()

Final touches

Axis labels

xlab("Your label\nsecond line") + ylab("Your label\nsecond line")

Axis limits: method 1

xlim(0, 3) + ylim(-20, 20)

Final touches

Axis limits: method 2 (good for publication)

scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0,0), limits = c(0,3))

where you replace continuous with the axis type (discrete, date, etc.)

Title

ggtitle("Your title\nsecond line\n")

Annotating

  • Personally, I prefer to annotate in Keynote
    • Save as a .pdf file
    • Drop straight into Endnote
    • Annotate with text
  • You can do this programatically, though it's a pain: + annotate("text", x = 4, y = 72, label = "your annotation", size = 4, colour = "red", angle = -27)
